<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Cover Crop Database: Complete Crop Summary of General</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR = #ffffff>

<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="/Images/cc_headr.gif" ALT="Working Icon">
<IMG SRC="/images/working.gif" ALT="Cover Crop Icon  " ALIGN="right">
<BR CLEAR=all><HR>
<A HREF = "#top"></A><H1>General</H1><HR>
<B><DL><DT><A HREF="/cgi-win/ccrop.exe/show_imgs_19">Images of General</A></B><BR></DL>
<B><DT>Effects on Water</B>
<DD>Erosion of soil, runoff water volume, and runoff content of nitrate, ammonia, and phosphorus were measured under four cover-cropping regimes preceding no-till soybean (<I>Glycine max</I></B> [L.] Merr.): (1) common chickweed (<I>Stellaria media</I></B> L., Caryophyllaceae); (2) Canada bluegrass (<I>Poa compressa</I></B> L., Poaceae); (3) downy brome (<I>Bromus tectorum</I></B> L., Poaceae); and (4) no cover crop (check).  The three regimes involving cover crops gave 31-40% greater vegetational cover (by cover crop + soybean) than did the check, and significantly reduced runoff and soil erosion.  There were no significant effects of cover regime on loss of dissolved nitrate, ammonia, or phosphate (Zhu et al., 1989).<P> Organic matter addition by green manuring does not directly affect all physical parameters.  Most likely to be increased are aggregate stability and bulk density, which may in turn improve water movement or retention.  These improvements do not necessarily occur.  It is rare that green manuring will increase soil organic matter; maintenance of organic matter will be attained in particular but ill-defined circumstances.  Even if soil physical condition is improved, increased crop yields may not occur.  Yield improvements resulting from improved soil structure are most likely when abnormal weather conditions prevail (MacRae and Mehuys, 1985).<P> Lloyd N.  Mielke (USDA-ARS, Soil and Water Conservation Research, East Campus, University of Nebraska, Lincoln, NE 68583, phone: 402-472-1516) has developed (in collaboration with Alice Jones [soil scientist] and Leonard Bashford [agricultural engineer] of the University of Nebraska) a modified sweep plough that loosens soil and increases water holding capacity while leaving cover-crop residues on the surface.  Earlier versions of the sweep plough caused sheer planes, which reduce infiltration of water and may interfere with root penetration.  A key feature of the current version is the presence of 6-inch-long steel shanks that break up soil in the sheer zone, and keep soil porous (Kaniuka, 1988).<P> Laboratory studies using double-tube apparatus showed that deep-rooted alfalfa can supply water to associated shallow-rooted maize during periods when water is in short supply in the shallow portions of the soil profile. This suggests that living mulches might do the same thing for associated economic crops (Corak et al., 1987).<P> Ten years of research has shown that vetch and rye mulch averaged 3.11 inches less water runoff per year than plowed unmulched corn (Hargrove, 1982).<P>
<B><DT>Effects on Soil</B>
<DD>Erosion of soil, runoff water volume, and runoff content of nitrate, ammonia, and phosphorus were measured under four cover-cropping regimes preceding no-till soybean (<I>Glycine max</I></B> [L.] Merr.): (1) common chickweed (<I>Stellaria media</I></B> L., Caryophyllaceae); (2) Canada bluegrass (<I>Poa compressa</I></B> L., Poaceae); (3) downy brome (<I>Bromus tectorum</I></B> L., Poaceae); and (4) no cover crop (check).  The three regimes involving cover crops gave 31-40% greater vegetational cover (by cover crop + soybean) than did the check, and they significantly reduced runoff and soil erosion.  There were no significant effects of cover regime on loss of dissolved nitrate, ammonia, or phosphate (Zhu et al., 1989).<P> Organic matter addition by green manuring does not directly affect all physical parameters.  Most likely to be increased are aggregate stability and bulk density, which may in turn improve water movement or retention.  These improvements do not necessarily occur.  It is rare that green manuring will increase soil organic matter; maintenance of organic matter will be attained in specific but ill-defined circumstances.  Even if soil physical condition is improved, increased crop yields may not occur.  Yield improvements resulting from improved soil structure are most likely when abnormal weather conditions prevail (MacRae and Mehuys, 1985).<P> Lloyd N.  Mielke (USDA-ARS, Soil and Water Conservation Research, East Campus, University of Nebraska, Lincoln, NE 68583, phone: 402-472-1516) has developed (in collaboration with Alice Jones [soil scientist] and Leonard Bashford [agricultural engineer] of the University of Nebraska) a modified sweep plough that loosens soil and increases water holding capacity while leaving cover-crop residues on the surface.  Earlier versions of the sweep plough caused sheer planes, which reduce infiltration of water and may interfere with root penetration.  A key feature of the current version is the presence of 6-inch-long steel shanks that break up soil in the sheer zone, and keep soil porous (Kaniuka, 1988).<P> In a review article, Hogue and Neilsen (1987) compared various effects of permanent vegetation (="grassed"), organic mulches, herbicides, and cultivation as approaches to managing orchard understories, effects on tree growth, yield, and soil were considered.  Overall considerations suggest that organic mulching in tree rows and grassed alleys may be the ideal approach, but that economics may dictate use of inorganic mulches or herbicides to suppress weeds in the tree row.  There is no consideration of the role of legumes in an orchard system, nor of the variability of different plant materials.<P> In a four-year field study in Nebraska, hairy vetch tilled under supplied N equivalent to or greater than 55 lb of fertilizer N per acre.  Hairy vetch managed without tillage contributed very little N, even after several years. Much of the N may have been lost by volatilization.  Contrasting results from the southeastern United States suggest that under warmer, more humid conditions, N mineralization from surface residues does provide substantial N to succeeding corn (Power et al., 1991).<P> Ten years of research has shown that vetch and rye mulch averaged 2.38 tons/a less soil erosion per year.  Mulched treatment of vetch and rye increased soil organic matter from 1.5 to 2.6%, and soil N from 0.47 to 0.069% after 10 years of continuous corn, while the plowed check remained at 1.2% organic matter and 0.036% N. (Hargrove, 1982)<P>
<B><DT>Incorporation</B>
<DD>Lloyd N.  Mielke (USDA-ARS, Soil and Water Conservation Research, East Campus, University of Nebraska, Lincoln, NE 68583, phone: 402-472-1516) has developed (in collaboration with Alice Jones [soil scientist] and Leonard Bashford [agricultural engineer] of the University of Nebraska) a modified sweep plough that loosens soil and increases water holding capacity while leaving cover-crop residues on the surface.  Earlier versions of the sweep plough caused sheer planes, which reduce infiltration of water and may interfere with root penetration.  A key feature of the current version is the presence of 6-inch-long steel shanks that break up soil in the sheer zone, and keep soil porous (Kaniuka, 1988).<P> Controlled chamber studies showed that surface (no-till) management of leguminous (lentil) residue can lead to 14% loss of N over 14 days (with air flow resulting in 0.5 displacements/minute).  There was a rapid early flush of ammonia volatilization, probably resulting from the decomposition of labile compounds, followed by a period of slower release, presumably resulting from gradual breakdown of more recalcitrant fractions. Incorporation of residue into the soil almost completely eliminated the volatilization (Janzen and McGinn, 1991).<P> A green manure is any crop incorporated before maturity.  These are mainly sources of organic matter and nitrogen.  Green manures are most effective when mixed in the upper few inches of soil. If incorporated too deeply, sufficient air will not be available for decomposition.  Green manures should be mowed and allowed to dry partially before being incorporated, to avoid putrefaction that can occur due to excess moisture.  If cover crops are incorporated while young and succulent, decomposition will be rapid because there is a low carbon:nitrogen ratio.  Therefore, microbes will sequester little of the nitrogen, and it will quickly become available to successive crops.  There will, however, be little accumulation of stable humus.  If incorporated during midseason, green manures will decompose more slowly, so nutrients will only become available later.  However, large amounts of organic matter are available, and soil structure will benefit more than if the green manure were young and succulent. Allowing cover crops to flower and mature partially prior to incorporation will lead to improved soil aeration. Carbon:nitrogen ratios will be high, leading to slow decomposition and protection of nutrients from leaching. Perennial sod crops become green manures when plowed under in advance of other crops (Gershuny and Smillie, 1986).<P> Cereal rye is difficult to incorporate (Schonbeck, 1988).<P>
<B><DT>Effects on Microclimate</B>
<DD>Vegetative bud development in the spring and fruit maturity were usually delayed on blueberry plants grown between sodded alleys (sown with <I>Festuca arundinacea</I></B> Schreb cv TK 31U) or with pine sawdust mulch.  Blueberry plants without sod or mulch had 88% and 79% of the fruit in the first harvest in 1985 and 1986, respectively, compared to 81% and 73% for plants with sod but no mulch (P=0.05) (Patten et al., 1989).<P>
<B><DT>Uses</B>
<DD>Low-growing perennial clovers may be used as living mulches between rows of economic crops (Gershuny and Smillie, 1986).<P> In a survey of 55 growers using cover crops in the northeastern United States:<P> 37 growers used cover crops to build soil fertility,<P> 15 used cover crops to improve soil structure and tilth,<P> 24 used cover crops to protect soil and prevent erosion,<P> 14 used cover crops to reduce the need for off-farm soil amendments,<P> 25 used leguminous cover crops as green manures to add soil nitrogen,<P> 5 used cover crops to make P and other nutrients more available,<P> 26 used cover crops for weed control,<P> 10 used cover crops to prepare new land for vegetable production,<P> 5 used cover crops for grain production,<P> 9 used cover crops for livestock feed,<P> 6 used cover crops for control of insect pests and diseases,<P> 3 used cover crops to reduce labor costs for tilling and weeding,<P> 8 used cover crops to prevent N leaching (Schonbeck, 1988).<P> The most common legume used in the Northeast is red clover. Smaller numbers of growers use alfalfa or sweetclovers (Schonbeck, 1988).<P>
<B><DT>Pest Effects, Nematodes</B>
<DD>Perennial cover crops are to be preferred over annual because large numbers of nematodes migrate from roots into soils after annuals mature (Marks and Townshend, 1973).<P> Many legumes are hosts to <I>Meloidogyne spp</I></B> (McKenry, pers. comm.).<P>
<B><DT>Root System</B>
<DD>Rooting depths in growth pouches (12 legumes evaluated) or in slant tubes (19 legumes evaluated) were positively correlated with performance in the field (up to at least 32 days after planting) (Brar et al., 1990).<P>
<B><DT>Inoculation</B>
<DD>Surface sowing of inoculated arrowleaf clover seed resulted in rapid decline in the densities of viable rhizobia, compared to seed planted at depths of 10 and 25 mm. Gum arabic was much better at promoting longevity of rhizobia than was water used as a sticker for the peat-based inoculum.  A streptomycin-resistant strain of rhizobia was used in this test, and water rinsate of the seed was plated out on a restrictive culture medium following serial dilution.  Colonies of rhizobia were evaluated two days later (Weaver and Holt, 1990).<P> Experimental  evidence  using  sterilized  and subsequently-reinoculated soil suggests that rhizobia are somewhat protected from predatory protozoans when secreted within soil aggregates of a diameter greater than 50 microns. However, in relatively wet soils, it may be less likely for them to find such microniches.  Also, other bacteria may compete for these microniches (Postma et al., 1989).<P> Based on tests of seed from collected from retail outlets throughout Kentucky, coating with CaCO3 of preinoculated seed leads to better performance of rhizobia for alfalfa, but not for red clover seed.  Performance was based on nodulation frequency and nitrogen content of plants grown in plastic growth pouches (3 seeds per pouch) with unsterilized soil (Vincent and Smith, 1982).<P> In this comparison of commercially- vs.  laboratory-produced inoculated, pelleted seed (coated with CaCO3) for effectiveness of nodulation and densities of rhizobia.  In general, commercially-inoculated seed had less than one hundredth as high a density of rhizobia as did the seed inoculated in the laboratory (Brockwell et al., 1975).  Inoculated, pelleted legume seed should always be sown as soon as possible after treatment and in any event before 4 weeks have elapsed.  Methyl cellulose can be substituted for gum arabic as an adhesive for inoculant (Anonymous, 1976).<P> Guidlines for inoculation, as presented by Anonymous (1976):<P> (1) Use a good commercial inoculant with the specific rhizobial type for the legume to be sown.  (2) Check expiration date, and do not use inoculant if the date has elapsed.  Ascertain that the inoculant has been stored in refrigeration.  (3) Use inoculant at the rate recommended by the manufacturer or at a higher rate (up to 4 X recommended rate).  (4) Mix inoculant and seed thoroughly, but without excess water.  (5) Hold inoculated seed in a cool, shady area.  Plant into a moist seedbed.  (6) Avoid drying seed: this will kill the rhizobia.  (7) Sow seed as soon as possible. Pellet seed if planting must be delayed, or if seeding is to be done into a dry seedbed, broadcast without being incorporated, or aerially seeded.  (8) Always pellet seed if the area to be seeded has abundant native legumes.  Use high rates of inoculum. Otherwise, the seeded legumes may be parasitized by incumbent rhizobia that are ineffective nodulators.  (9) Do not mix acid, or trace-nutrient-containing fertilizers or pesticides with inoculated legume seed.  Do not treat inoculated seed with herbicides, fungicides, or insecticides.  Most of these are highly toxic to rhizobia.  (10) Phosphorus and sulfur are the elements most commonly deficient in Californian rangeland soils. Be sure that these are adequately available.  (11) Avoid the use of nitrogen fertilizers.  (12) A good legume stand should have at least 20 plants per square foot.  (13) After legumes have produced three or four leaves, excavate a few plants and check for nodulation.  Lack of nodules usually indicates faulty technique.  A few large nodules that are pink inside and located on the crown or in the upper roots indicate early, effective nodulation.  Many small, white nodules over the entire root system indicate ineffective nodulation by resident rhizobia. To pellet seed:<P> (1) Use fresh inoculant, and use 4 X the amount recommended. Use gum arabic (without preservatives) at least fine enough to pass through 8-mesh screen; dissolve 4 lb of gum arabic per gallon of water.  Use finely-ground calcium carbonate (CaCO3) (80% should pass through a 200-mesh screen).  (2) For vetch, 100 lb of seed requires 21/2 quarts of the gum arabic solution and 30 lb of calcium carbonate.  For 100 lb of seed of subterranean, rose, or crimson clovers, 5 quarts of solution and 50 lb of calcium carbonate are required. For 100 lb of alfalfa or bur clover seed, 5 quarts of gum arabic solution and 40 lb of calcium carbonate are needed.  (3) Dissolve gum arabic in hot water: do not boil.  It will dissolve in about 30 minutes in hot water or overnight in cold water.  Cool the solution.  Add the correct amount of inoculant and stir into a smooth slurry.  Immediately pour the seed into a cement mixer, add the gum-inoculant mixture, and rotate at high speed until all seeds are coated.  While the mixer is running, add all the calcium carbonate at once. After all lots have been run, clean the mixer by running a load of water and gravel through it. Pellets allowed to sit for 24 hours are firmer, and will perform better in a seed drill.  Screen or winnow the seed to remove excess calcium carbonate.  Do not use vigorous agitators in the seeding equipment, because these may damage the pellet coatings.<P> Note from R.L.  Bugg: An easier alternative to all these things is to use the PelGel/Pelinoc system from Nitragin, per the printed instructions (Holland et al., 1969).<P> Guidelines for inoculating legumes were provided by Anonymous (no year given):<P> (1) Use specific inoculant type for the crop to be seeded.  (2) Check expiration date on inoculant.  When using pre-inoculated (e.g., pelleted) seed, check expiration date and seed as soon as possible.  If in doubt, to ensure viability of rhizobia, reinoculate.  (3) Store inoculant in cool location and do not expose to sunlight.  (4) Use a ratio of 1:10 sticker to water. Corn syrup, sugar, powdered milk, or commercial stickers can be used. (5) For adverse or dryland situations, apply inoculant at twice the recommended rate.  (6) If legume plants are stunted or yellowish, this may indicate a nitrogen deficiency and probably failure of inoculation.  Pink to red nodules indicate nitrogen fixation. Green nodules are not active, and white nodules are ineffective .<P> Anonymous (no year given) continued that nitrogen fixation is the conversion of atmospheric nitrogen (N-2) to ammonia nitrogen (NH3). During the establishment of the legume-rhizobia symbiosis, rhizobia multiply in the root zone, invade root hairs, follow an infection thread into the root proper, and then multiply along with root cells to form a nodule.  Thereafter, fixation of nitrogen begins. If inoculant is applied to the legume seed prior to sowing, this is termed the seed applied method.  If inoculant is metered into the furrow during seeding, this is termed the direct soil method.<P> Anonymous (no year given) wrote that ineffective or inefficient resident rhizobia may colonize legumes that are seeded without having been properly inoculated.  To check for effective nodulation, wait about 50 days after germination and excavate plants carefully, to avoid damaging nodules.  Nodules should be abundant around the taproot and have a pink to beefsteak-red color inside.  Molybdenum can be a limiting element in nitrogen fixation, particularly if it is unavailable due to low soil pH. The advantages of inoculating legumes are most clear the first year that legume is seeded in a particular field.  Sometimes the advantages are not visible in the field but only become apparent after harvest and weighing.  Peat-based legume inoculants show better survival of rhizobia than do agar, broth, or freeze-dried cultures.  Direct soil inoculation systems can employ either granular or liquid rhizobial formulations.  The former is easier to use and can avoid the contact of rhizobia with fungicide-treated seed.  It is also important to growers using air or plateless planters.  Seed applied delivery or inoculation systems include planter box, preinoculated seed, and custom inoculation. Planter box inoculation involves mixing the inoculant and seed in the hopper and can involve dry (dry method) or moistened (sprinkle method) peat-based inoculant or the use of a slurry (slurry method) including the inoculant, water, and perhaps stickers such as NitraCoat or NutriGum (both produced by Nitragin) to improve adherence and survival of rhizobia. Pre-inoculation of legume seed is done prior to sale to the grower.  This approach is fraught with uncertainty as to the viability of the rhizobia because the grower usually cannot be sure of the time elapsed since incoculation nor of the conditions under which the inoculated seed was subsequently stored.  Custom inoculation can have the same disadvantages but usually is under closer control by the grower.  The Pelinoc System (Nitragin) appears particularly effective and involves the use of a fine-mesh peat-based inoculant and a nutrient-rich sticker called PelGel.  This approach supplies high densities of rhizobia and extends the viability of rhizobia even in hot, dry soils.  This method is compatible with cyclone or aerial seeding.<P> Nitragin Company, Inc.  (no date) advised that growers should keep the following guidelines in mind: (1) Rhizobia are perishable; growers should carefully consider expiration dates on packages of rhizobial inoculant.  (2) Peat is the best carrier for maintaining rhizobial viability.  (3) Make sure that there is sufficient inoculant for the amount of seed that must be sown. (4) Avoid mixing fungicides and other chemicals with inoculants, and avoid pre-mixed products.  (5) Store inoculant in cool areas and out of sunlight. Do not leave inoculants ovenight in planting equipment. (6) Make sure that the correct inoculant type is used for the legume to be planted.  (7) Get recommmendations from Cooperative Extension specialists or county agents, preferably based on findings from local or regional tests.<P> Jones et al.  (1978) wrote that the "PELGEL-PELINOC" system is a proprietary system (Nitragin Co.) of inoculation seed using a sticker with a gum-arabic base and peat moss inoculum (50g/kg seed) for coating and drying instead of limestone.  The sticker is called "PELGEL" and the inoculum "PELINOC".<P> Graves (1986) related that the PELINOC-PELGEL inoculation system was developed by Dr.  Joseph Burton of The Nitragin Company.  It is a "do-it- yourself" system designed to be used on farm, and is easier, costs less, and makes a more durable product than the pellet-inoculation system described in AXT-280 that Cooperative Extension agents have been recommending. A total of about 6 lbs of dry weight PELINOC-PELGEL materials are added per 100 lbs of seed. Data from Mendocino and Butte Counties showed PELINOC-PELGEL be consistently superior to the method described in AXT-280.<P> According to the account by the Nitragin Co.  (1975), the Australians were pioneers in establishing legumes on rough, infertile, acid soils where they had to grow clover to feed livestock.  Large peat base inocula were required and a concentrated gum solution was needed to stick the inoculum to the seed. Five quarts of the inoculant-gum slurry was mixed with 100 lbs of seed.  The wetted seeds were then dried by mixing quickly with 60 lbs of very finely pulverized limestone in a small concrete mixer.  The limestone coated the seed.  This method of inoculation is called "lime-pelleting". "Lime-pelleting" is a good method of inoculating seed, but it has several disadvantages: (1) it requires machinery; (2) it almost doubles the weight of the seed; (3) the coated seeds are very abrasive and cause excessive wear on drilling equipment; (4) the heavy coating of limestone actually gives little protection to the nodule bacteria and is so slowly soluble that it has little effect on soil acidity; and (5) it is very expensive. Nonetheless, the results from the "lime-pelleting" inoculation under Australian conditions more than justifies the inconvenience and cost.  The PELINOC system has many advantages over the "lime-pelleting" method: (1) it provides more viable rhizobia on the seed and they survive in greater quantities; (2) it supplies sufficient soluble calcium to neutralize acidity in the microenvironment of the planted seed; (3) it increases weight of the seed by only about 5% and the seeds are easily planted with regular equipment; (4) it is easy to apply and requires no special machinery; and (5) it can be applied by the grower just before planting to assure large numbers of viable rhizobia on the planted seed.  Seed should be inoculated at least one-half hour before planting and may be safely inoculated the day before providing they are stored in a cool place.<P>
<B><DT>Non-N Nutrient Contribution</B>
<DD>In a survey of 55 growers in the northeastern United States, 5 used cover crops to make P and other nutrients more available (Schonbeck, 1988).<P>
<B><DT>Pest Effects, Weeds</B>
<DD>In a survey of 55 growers in the northeastern United States, 26 used cover crops for weed control (Schonbeck, 1988).<P> Weed above-ground biomass data (dry) were taken in a replicated study (r=4) at Blue Heron Vineyard (Fetzer Vineyards), Hopland, Mendocino County, California.  Cover crops were seeded in late October, 1990; harvest was on May 15-16, 1991.  Dominant winter annual weeds were chickweed, shepherds purse, rattail fescue, and annual ryegrass.  The F-test for effect due to cover crop yielded P=0.0001.  Means separated by less than Fisher's protected least significant difference (1.963) are deemed not significantly different (at the P=0.05 level).  Data were as follows (Mg/ha, Mean +/- S.E.M.):<P> 'KOALA' SUBCLOVER: 0.086+/-0.086<P> COMMON VETCH: 0.303+/-0.279<P> 'DALKEITH' SUBCLOVER: 2.297+/-0.036<P> 'TRIKKALA' SUBCLOVER: 1.608+/-0.694<P> 'MT.  BARKER' SUBCLOVER: 0.581+/-0.269<P> 'SEATON PARK' SUBCLOVER: 0.951+/-0.391<P> 'HYKON' ROSE CLOVER: 1.977+/-0.992<P> 'LANA' VETCH: 0.000+/-0.000<P> PURPLE VETCH: 0.717+/-0.566<P> 'AUSTRIAN WINTER' PEA: 0.312+/-0.258<P> 'FLAME'CRIMSON CLOVER: 0.607+/-0.153<P> BIENNIAL SWEETCLOVERS: 3.274+/-0.562<P> BROADLEAF BIRDSFOOT TREFOIL: 2.372+/-0.928<P> BERSEEM CLOVER: 0.167+/-0.104<P> LADINO CLOVER: 2.829+/-0.659<P> 'HANNAFORD' BARREL MEDIC: 0.958+/-0.532<P> BELL BEAN (NO NAMED CULTIVAR): 0.664+/-0.308<P> 'SALINA' STRAWBERRY CLOVER: 3.540+/-0.704<P> 'CIRCLE VALLEY' BURCLOVER: 0.896+/-0.609<P> MEADOW BARLEY: 2.199+/-1.228<P> BLUE WILDRYE (BERKELEY FORM): 0.501+/-0.378<P> BLUE WILDRYE (ANDERSON FORM): 1.256+/-0.348<P> CALIFORNIA BROME: 1.256+/-0.745<P> 'MOLATE' RED FESCUE: 2.873+/-0.971<P> 'BLANDO' BROME: 0.420+/-0.215<P> annual ryegrass ("oregon common"): 2.477+/-2.477<P> BARLEY ('UC 476'): 0.043_.0430<P> 'MERCED' CEREAL RYE: 0.031+/-0.031<P> 'CALIFORNIA RED' OAT: 0.241+/-0.083<P> 'ZORRO' FESCUE: 0.791+/-0.444<P> BLACK MUSTARD: 1.015+/-0.437<P> CONTROL: 4.917+/-1.010 (Bugg et al., unpublished data).<P> Vegetational cover data for cover crops, Blue Heron Vineyard, Hopland, Mendocino County, California, May, 1991.  For F-test of effect due to cover crops, P=0.0001.  Means separated by less than Fisher's protected least significant difference (17.982) are deemed not significantly different (at the P=0.05 level).  % vegetational cover for the various cover crops were as follows (Mean +/- S.E.M.):<P> 'KOALA' SUBCLOVER: 94.50+/-3.33<P> COMMON VETCH: 100.00+/-0.00<P> 'DALKEITH' SUBCLOVER: 87.50+/-4.33<P> 'TRIKKALA' SUBCLOVER: 96.25+/-1.25<P> 'MT.  BARKER' SUBCLOVER: 96.25+/-1.25<P> 'SEATON PARK' SUBCLOVER: 92.50+/-2.50<P> 'HYKON' ROSE CLOVER: 83.75+/-8.00<P> 'LANA' VETCH: 97.50+/-2.50<P> PURPLE VETCH: 95.00+/-2.04<P> 'AUSTRIAN WINTER' PEA: 96.25+/-3.75<P> 'FLAME'CRIMSON CLOVER: 71.50+/-17.12<P> BIENNIAL SWEETCLOVERS: 41.25+/-13.29<P> BROADLEAF BIRDSFOOT TREFOIL: 32.50+/-5.95<P> BERSEEM CLOVER: 98.75+/-1.25<P> LADINO CLOVER: 77.50+/-3.23<P> 'HANNAFORD' BARREL MEDIC: 95.00+/-2.04<P> BELL BEAN (NO NAMED CULTIVAR): 85.00+/-7.36<P> 'SALINA' STRAWBERRY CLOVER: 62.50+/-10.51<P> 'CIRCLE VALLEY' BURCLOVER: 73.00+/-18.70<P> MEADOW BARLEY: 53.75+/-7.47<P> BLUE WILDRYE (BERKELEY FORM): 67.50+/-4.79<P> BLUE WILDRYE (ANDERSON FORM): 78.75+/-1.25<P> CALIFORNIA BROME: 96.25+/-2.39<P> 'MOLATE' RED FESCUE: 13.75+/-2.39<P> 'BLANDO' BROME: 92.50+/-1.44<P> ANNUAL RYEGRASS ("OREGON COMMON"): 100.00+/-0.00<P> BARLEY ('UC 476'): 87.50+/-6.61<P> 'MERCED' CEREAL RYE: 96.25+/-2.39<P> 'CALIFORNIA RED' OAT: 98.75+/-1.25<P> 'ZORRO' FESCUE: 93.75+/-3.75<P> BLACK MUSTARD: 91.25+/-5.54<P> CONTROL: 100.00+/-0.00 (Bugg et al., unpublished data)<P>
<B><DT>Effects on Livestock</B>
<DD>In a survey of 55 growers in the northeastern United States, 9 used cover crops for livestock feed (Schonbeck, 1988).<P>
<B><DT>Pest Effects, Diseases</B>
<DD>In a survey of 55 growers in the northeastern United States, 6 used cover crops for control of insect pests and diseases (Schonbeck, 1988).<P>
<B><DT>Effects on Workers</B>
<DD>In a survey of 55 growers in the northeastern United States, 3 used cover crops to reduce labor costs for tilling and weeding (Schonbeck, 1988).<P>
<B><DT>Nutrients</B>
<DD>The addition of the equivalent of 31 kg/ha of starter nitrogen did not reduce nitrogen fixation by arrowleaf clover, and substantially improved seedling vigor.  Starter nitrogen can actually lead to improved nitrogen fixation by legumes (Schomberg and Weaver, 1990).<P>
<B><DT>N Contribution</B>
<DD>The addition of the equivalent of 31 kg/ha of starter nitrogen did not reduce nitrogen fixation by arrowleaf clover and substantially improved seedling vigor.  Starter nitrogen can actually lead to improved nitrogen fixation by legumes (Schomberg and Weaver, 1990).<P> Controlled chamber studies showed that surface (no-till) management of leguminous (lentil) residue can lead to 14% loss of N over 14 days (with air flow resulting in 0.5 displacements/minute).  There was a rapid early flush of ammonia volatilization, probably resulting from the decomposition of labile compounds, followed by a period of slower release, presumably resulting from gradual breakdown of more recalcitrant fractions. Incorporation of residue into the soil almost completely eliminated the volatilization (Janzen and McGinn, 1991).<P> In a survey of 55 growers in the northeastern United States, 25 used leguminous cover crops as green manures to add soil nitrogen (Schonbeck, 1988).<P> In a survey of 55 growers in the northeastern United States, 8 used cover crops to prevent N leaching (Schonbeck, 1988).<P> In a four-year field study in Nebraska, hairy vetch tilled under supplied N equivalent to or greater than 55 lb of fertilizer N per acre.  Hairy vetch managed without tillage contributed very little N, even after several years. Much of the N may have been lost by volatilization.  Contrasting results from the southeastern United States suggest that under warmer, more humid conditions, N mineralization from surface residues does provide substantial N to succeeding corn (Power et al., 1991).<P> It appears that nitrogen applied to corn can be reduced by 50 to 80 lbs/acre when a legume cover crop is used (Hargrove, 1982).<P> In order for N mineralization to occur, N concentration of incorporated residue must exceed 15-25 g/kg.  However, little mineralization will occur if there are high concentrations of lignin or polyphenols.  In a study involving the decomposition of and N mineralization from residues of 6 kinds of legumes (alfalfa, round leaf cassia, leucaena, Fitzroy stylo, snail medic, and <I>Vigna trilobata</I></B>, the ratio of (lignin+polyphenols):N was a good predictor of N mineralization rate, whereas initial N concentration of residues was not.  After 12 weeks, net N mineralized ranged from 11% from round leaf cassia to 47% for alfalfa (Fox et al., 1990).<P>
<B><DT>Mixtures</B>
<DD>Harry Shorey's experiments have shown that in cover-cropped vineyards, leafhopper populations remained stable through the season but in bare orchards increased to about 180 per 30 leaves. The reason for reduction in cover-cropped vineyards is not clear; predatory insects and spiders, though abundant in the cover crops themselves, were scarce in the vines.  Shorey saw similar patterns whether understories have sown cover crops mixtures or resident vegetation (weeds), but would not use just one cover crop (e.g., buckwheat) (Renn, 1991).<P> Paul Buxman uses mixtures of 7 or 8 legumes and grasses in his vineyard (Renn, 1991).<P>
<B><DT>Pest Effects, Insects</B>
<DD>Harry Shorey's experiments have shown that in cover-cropped vineyards, leafhopper populations remained stable through the season but in bare vineyards increased to about 180 per 30 leaves. The reason for reduction in cover-cropped vineyards is not clear; predatory insects and spiders, though abundant in the cover crops themselves, were scarce in the vines.  Shorey saw similar patterns whether understories have sown cover crops mixtures or resident vegetation (weeds), but he would not use just one cover crop (e.g., buckwheat) (Renn, 1991).<P> Convergent lady beetle (<I>Hippodamia convergens</I></B> Guerin-Meneville) and <I>Olla abdominalis</I></B> (Say) (now termed <I>O.  v-nigrum</I></B> [Mulsant]) were the two most abundant Coccinellidae attacking walnut aphid (<I>Chromaphis juglandicola</I></B> [Kaltenbach]) in northern Californian groves of Persian walnut. Gound cover (unspecified composition) can assist biological control by convergent lady beetle because it harbors aphids (which serve as alternate prey) from late February through April or May.  If ground cover is disked or chopped too early, beetles will emigrate before walnut aphid is available. Such disengagement of the predators can lead to eruptions of the aphid. Chopping of understory cover killed many lady beetles, but some, including pupae, survived.  The retention of lady beetles in close proximity to walnut trees is probably more important than production of large numbers of beetles (Sluss, 1967).<P> In a survey of 55 growers in the northeastern United States, 6 used cover crops for control of insect pests and diseases (Schonbeck, 1988).<P> Tarnished plant bug, <I>Lygus lineolaris</I></B> (Palisot de Beauvois) and stink bugs (Hemiptera: Pentatomidae) cause catfacing damage to peaches and are abundant on flowering winter-annual weeds in the orchard understories.  The present unreplicated study indicated greater damage in an orchard with a weedy understory than in weed-free (herbicided with Simazine) orchard (Johnson, 1989).<P> Wireworms were encountered in a significantly higher proportion of cornfields with a prior cropping history of sod.  No data on damage or economics were presented (Belcher, 1989).<P> In North Carolinian peach orchards, weedy plots dominated by chickweed and Carolina geranium showed higher percentages of catfacing damage to fruits, caused by hemipteran insects (<I>Lygus lineolaris</I></B> and several types of stink bug).  In 1986, catfacing damage was 8.9% in weedy plots vs.  2.6% and 2.2% in plots with no winter annuals and bare ground.  The corresponding values for 1987 were 28.2%, 14.4%, and 10.2% (Meagher and Meyer, 1990).<P> Tarnished plant bug, <I>Lygus lineolaris</I></B> (Palisot de Beauvois); stink bugs (dusky stink bug, <I>Euschistus tristigmus</I></B> [Say]; brown stink bug, <I>E. servus</I></B> [Say]; green stink bug, <I>Acrosternum hilare</I></B> [Say]; and <I>Brochymena arborea</I></B> [Hemiptera: Pentatomidae]) cause catfacing damage to peaches and are abundant on flowering winter-annual weeds in the orchard understories.  A previous study by Meyer (1984) (Proceedings of the Southeastern Peach Convention) indicated that suppression of understory winter annuals reduced incidence of catfacing.  The present study, though unreplicated, confirmed this finding (Johnson, 1988).<P>
<B><DT>Maximum Height</B>
<DD>Heights of cover crops were measured in a replicated study (r=4) at the Blue Heron Vineyard (Fetzer Vineyards), Hopland, Mendocino County, California, May 2, 1991.  The F-test for effect due to cover crop yielded P=0.0001.  Means separated by less than Fisher's protected least significant difference (16.694) are deemed not significantly different (at the P=0.05 level). Heights for the various cover crops were as follows (cm, Mean +/- S.E.M.):<P> 'KOALA' SUBCLOVER: 45.72+/-2.93<P> COMMON VETCH: 54.61+/-3.02<P> 'DALKEITH' SUBCLOVER: 31.75+/-1.27<P> 'TRIKKALA' SUBCLOVER: 43.82+/-1.60<P> 'MT.  BARKER' SUBCLOVER: 36.83+/-2.64<P> 'SEATON PARK' SUBCLOVER: 37.47+/-2.40<P> 'HYKON' ROSE CLOVER: 43.18+/-3.28<P> 'LANA' VETCH: 67.31+/-4.21<P> PURPLE VETCH: 57.15+/-4.46<P> 'AUSTRIAN WINTER' PEA: 66.68+/-4.32<P> 'FLAME'CRIMSON CLOVER: 48.90+/-15.77<P> BIENNIAL SWEETCLOVERS: 22.23+/-5.81<P> BROADLEAF BIRDSFOOT TREFOIL: 19.05+/-2.43<P> BERSEEM CLOVER: 57.15+/-3.20<P> LADINO CLOVER: 33.02+/-3.28<P> 'HANNAFORD' BARREL MEDIC: 40.01+/-1.91<P> BELL BEAN (NO NAMED CULTIVAR): 121.92+/-10.78<P> 'SALINA' STRAWBERRY CLOVER: 31.12+/-4.91<P> 'CIRCLE VALLEY' BURCLOVER: 34.93+/-5.43<P> MEADOW BARLEY: 70.49+/-5.43<P> BLUE WILDRYE (BERKELEY FORM): 76.20+/-2.07<P> BLUE WILDRYE (ANDERSON FORM): 72.39+/-3.36<P> CALIFORNIA BROME: 95.89+/-0.64<P> 'BLANDO' BROME (SOFT CHESS): 100.97+/-2.17<P> ANNUAL RYEGRASS ("OREGON COMMON"): 92.08+/-4.20<P> BARLEY ('UC 476'): 94.62+/-6.17<P> 'MERCED' CEREAL RYE: 148.59+/-7.59<P> 'CALIFORNIA RED' OAT: 109.22+/-3.74<P> 'ZORRO' FESCUE: 60.33+/-12.59<P> BLACK MUSTARD: 171.45+/-11.00 (Bugg et al., unpublished data)<P>
<B><DT>Biomass</B>
<DD>Above-ground biomass harvests were made on May 15-16, 1991 for cover crops seeded during October, 1990, in a replicated study (r=4) at Blue Heron Vineyard, Fetzer Vineyards, Hopland, Mendocino County, California.  Weeds in Control were regarded as a cover crop.  The F-test for effect due to cover crop yielded P=0.0001. Means separated by less than Fisher's protected least significant difference (4.302) are deemed not significantly different (at the P=0.05 level ) .  Means for the various cover crops were as follows (Mg/ha, Mean +/- S.E.M., r=4):<P> 'KOALA' SUBCLOVER: 9.663+/-1.605<P> COMMON VETCH: 8.912+/-0.950<P> 'DALKEITH' SUBCLOVER: 5.134+/-1.842<P> 'TRIKKALA' SUBCLOVER: 8.281+/-1.371<P> 'MT.  BARKER' SUBCLOVER: 7.628+/-0.988<P> 'SEATON PARK' SUBCLOVER: 6.814+/-0.378<P> 'HYKON' ROSE CLOVER: 6.153+/-1.672<P> 'LANA' VETCH: 9.180+/-0.933<P> PURPLE VETCH: 10.117+/-0.535<P> 'AUSTRIAN WINTER' PEA: 6.891+/-0.744<P> 'FLAME'CRIMSON CLOVER: 8.456+/-1.477<P> BIENNIAL SWEETCLOVERS: 1.656+/-0.626<P> BROADLEAF BIRDSFOOT TREFOIL: 6.443+/-3.989<P> BERSEEM CLOVER: 8.463+/-0.803<P> LADINO CLOVER: 3.941+/-0.872<P> 'HANNAFORD' BARREL MEDIC: 7.782+/-0.791<P> BELL BEAN (NO NAMED CULTIVAR): 7.728+/-1.230<P> 'SALINA' STRAWBERRY CLOVER: 1.866+/-0.607<P> 'CIRCLE VALLEY' BURCLOVER: 8.352+/-1.836<P> MEADOW BARLEY: 3.712+/-0.445<P> BLUE WILDRYE (BERKELEY FORM): 5.010+/-0.580<P> BLUE WILDRYE (ANDERSON FORM): 7.501+/-1.720<P> CALIFORNIA BROME: 8.586+/-1.220<P> 'MOLATE' RED FESCUE: 2.082+/-1.853<P> 'BLANDO' BROME: 9.450+/-1.438<P> ANNUAL RYEGRASS ("OREGON COMMON"): 8.513+/-3.258<P> BARLEY ('UC 476'): 12.942+/-2.643<P> 'MERCED' CEREAL RYE: 9.880+/-1.789<P> 'CALIFORNIA RED' OAT: 2.534+/-1.429<P> 'ZORRO' FESCUE: 7.493+/-0.873<P> BLACK MUSTARD: 10.907+/-1.546<P> CONTROL: 4.918+/-1.010 (Bugg et al., unpublished data)<P> Total biomass data (dry, cover crop + weeds) were measured at the Blue Heron Vineyard, Hopland, Mendocino County, California, May 15-16, 1991. The F-test for effect due to cover crop yielded P=0.0026. Fisher's protected least significant difference=4.037. Means separated by less than this are deemed not significantly different (at the P=0.05 level ).  Above-ground biomass data for the various cover crops were as follows (Mg/ha, Mean +/- S.E.M.):<P> 'KOALA' SUBCLOVER: 9.750+/-1.595<P> COMMON VETCH: 9.214+/-0.695<P> 'DALKEITH' SUBCLOVER: 7.431+/-1.866<P> 'TRIKKALA' SUBCLOVER: 9.890+/-1.427<P> 'MT.  BARKER' SUBCLOVER: 8.209+/-0.851<P> 'SEATON PARK' SUBCLOVER: 7.765+/-0.487<P> 'HYKON' ROSE CLOVER: 8.130+/-2.198<P> 'LANA' VETCH: 9.180+/-0.933<P> PURPLE VETCH: 10.834+/-0.810<P> 'AUSTRIAN WINTER' PEA: 7.203+/-0.654<P> 'FLAME'CRIMSON CLOVER: 9.063+/-1.540<P> BIENNIAL SWEETCLOVERS: 4.930+/-0.620<P> BROADLEAF BIRDSFOOT TREFOIL: 8.815+/-3.409<P> BERSEEM CLOVER: 8.630+/-0.713<P> LADINO CLOVER: 6.771+/-1.242<P> 'HANNAFORD' BARREL MEDIC: 8.739+/-0.417<P> BELL BEAN (NO NAMED CULTIVAR): 8.392+/-1.360<P> 'SALINA' STRAWBERRY CLOVER: 5.405+/-0.620<P> 'CIRCLE VALLEY' BURCLOVER: 9.248+/-1.403<P> MEADOW BARLEY: 5.912+/-1.330<P> BLUE WILDRYE (BERKELEY FORM): 6.511+/-0.661<P> BLUE WILDRYE (ANDERSON FORM): 8.757+/-1.790<P> CALIFORNIA BROME: 9.842+/-1.928<P> 'MOLATE' RED FESCUE: 4.954+/-1.157<P> 'BLANDO' BROME: 9.870+/-1.634<P> ANNUAL RYEGRASS ("OREGON COMMON"): 10.990+/-1.642<P> BARLEY ('UC 476'): 12.985+/-2.621<P> 'MERCED' CEREAL RYE: 9.910+/-1.775<P> 'CALIFORNIA RED' OAT: 12.775+/-1.410<P> 'ZORRO' FESCUE: 8.284+/-0.958<P> BLACK MUSTARD: 11.922+/-1.381<P> CONTROL: 4.917+/-1.010 (Bugg et al., unpublished data)<P>
<B><DT>Common Name</B>
<DD>No information is available in this database on this topic.<P>
<B><DT>Scientific Name</B>
<DD>No information is available in this database on this topic.<P>
<B><DT>Cultivar</B>
<DD>No information is available in this database on this topic.<P>
<B><DT>Seed Description</B>
<DD>No information is available in this database on this topic.<P>
<B><DT>Seedling Description</B>
<DD>No information is available in this database on this topic.<P>
<B><DT>Mature Plant Description</B>
<DD>No information is available in this database on this topic.<P>
<B><DT>Temperature</B>
<DD>No information is available in this database on this topic.<P>
<B><DT>Geographic Range</B>
<DD>No information is available in this database on this topic.<P>
<B><DT>Water</B>
<DD>Cover crops require water, but also may condition soil to improved water infiltration; used as mulches, cover crop residues can reduce evapotranspiration rates (Bugg, pers. comm.).<P>
<B><DT>Soil pH</B>
<DD>Leguminous cover crops through their nitrogen fixation, produce hydronium ions and thereby lower soil pH.  However, the addition of soil organic matter buffers this to some extent (Bugg, pers.).<P>
<B><DT>Soil Type</B>
<DD>Cover crops are available for most soil types.<P>
<B><DT>Shade Tolerance</B>
<DD>Cover crops vary greatly in their shade tolerance.  Especially intolerant are buckwheat and sesbania.  Especially tolerant are cowpea, hyacinth bean, and bur medic (Bugg, pers. comm.).<P>
<B><DT>Salinity Tolerance</B>
<DD>Cover crops vary greatly in their salinity tolerance. Especially tolerant are barley, 'Salina' strawberry clover, white and yellow sweetclovers, and sourclover.  Especially intolerant are bur medic and field pea (Bugg, pers. comm.).<P>
<B><DT>Herbicide Sensitivity</B>
<DD>Cover crops vary greatly in their sensitivities to herbicides. Subterranean clovers are relatively tolerant of glyphosate; many legumes, once established, are tolerant of 2,4-DB.  Various herbicides are categorized based on their suitability for controlling grasses or broadleaf weeds.  Thus, some selectivity is possible (Bugg, pers. comm.).<P>
<B><DT>Life Cycle</B>
<DD>Cover crops vary in their life cycles.  Cool-season annual plants are typically sown in the autumn, and flower and senesce in the spring and early summer.  Warm-season annuals are sown after the threat of frost is past, flower during the summer, and senesce or are frost-killed in the fall or winter.  Biennial species include certain Brassicaceae and Fabaceae that grow vegetatively the first year and flower and senenesce the second year. Perennial species may show either cool- or warm-season growth, or both.  In some cases, seasonal dormancy may be induced by lack of water, cold, heat, or photoperiod.  Some plants may behave as annuals or perennials in different parts of their geographic ranges, or under different management regimes.  Some cover crops are self-regenerating; others require reseeding by the farmer.  Again, management regime may determine which is the case (Bugg, pers. comm.).<P>
